-- Italian Stocks Advance; Atlantia, Eni, Mediaset, Mediobanca, Safilo Move
-- B y   F r a n c e s c a   C i n e l l i
-- 2010-10-28T15:46:46Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-28/acea-banco-popolare-cir-eni-shares-might-move-italian-equity-preview.html
Italy’s benchmark FTSE MIB Index
ended three days of declines, rising 258.80, or 1.2 percent, to
21,509.62 at the 5:30 p.m. close in Milan.  The following stocks were among the most active in the
Italian market today.  Amplifon SpA  (AMP IM) rose 1.8 percent to 3.85 euros, the
highest level since Aug. 9. The world’s largest hearing-aid
distributor said nine-month net income rose to 15.5 million
euros ($21.5 million) from 13 million euros.  Atlantia SpA  (ATL IM) jumped 2.1 percent to 16.34 euros, a
second day of gains. Sintonia SA said it purchased an additional
3.2 percent stake in Italy’s largest toll-road operator from
Aabar Infrastructure Gmbh for 309.6 million euros, boosting its
holding to 42.2 percent.  Eni SpA  (ENI IM) surged 2.8 percent to 16.15 euros, ending
four days of declines. Europe’s fourth-largest oil company
reported third-quarter net income of 1.72 billion euros, beating
the 1.29 billion-euro average estimate of six analysts in a
Bloomberg survey.  Luxottica Group SpA  (LUX IM) gained 1.1 percent to 21.29
euros. Goldman Sachs Group Inc. increased its price estimate to
25.40 euros from 22.70 euros.  Mediaset SpA  (MS IM) gained 3.9 percent to 5.22 euros, its
first increase this week. Gestevision Telecinco SA, The Spanish
TV station that’s 50.1 percent owned by Mediaset, reported nine-
month operating profit and sales that beat analysts’ estimates
on rising advertising sales.  Mediobanca SpA  (MB IM) advanced 1.9 percent to 7.52 euros,
the highest price in six months. The investment bank posted a
smaller decline in quarterly earnings than analysts estimated,
as all its units turned a profit for the first time in 18
months. Net income fell to 128 million euros in the three months
ended Sept. 30 from 201 million euros a year earlier, the Milan-
based lender said.  Safilo Group SpA  (SFL IM) rose 2.9 percent to 11.41 euros,
a first gain in three days. Deutsche Bank AG reiterated a
“buy” rating on the world’s second-largest maker of glasses
ahead of results, due Nov. 5. The brokerage also said that it
expects Safilo “to unveil a detailed business plan soon, which
could be a key catalyst as it would likely substantiate market
expectations for the outer years.”  Saipem SpA  (SPM IM) rose 1.3 percent to 31.83 euros,
gaining for a second day. Europe’s largest oilfield-services
provider had its price estimate upgraded to 40 euros at Barclays
Plc, 37 euros at CA Cheuvreux SA, 34.50 euros at Royal Bank of
Scotland Group Plc, 33 euros at Nomura Holdings Inc. and BofA
Merrill Lynch Global Research and 32 euros at Credit Suisse
Group AG.  STMicroelectronics NV  (STM IM) advanced 2.9 percent to 6.32
euros, extending yesterday’s 4.2 percent gain. Deutsche Bank AG
upgraded the stock to “buy” from “hold,” suggesting that
investors “buy ahead of the first-quarter trough.”  Telecom Italia SpA  (TIT IM), Italy’s biggest phone company,
advanced 2 percent to 1.11 euros. Telecommunication shares rose
in Europe after France Telecom SA, France’s largest phone
company, posted profit that topped analysts’ projections.  Tenaris SpA  (TEN IM), the world’s biggest maker of seamless
steel tubes, climbed 2.1 percent to 14.92 euros, snapping two
days of losses. Crude oil rose in New York after a government
report showed that U.S. initial jobless claims fell last week to
the lowest level in three months.  Tod’s SpA  (TOD IM) added 1.5 percent to 69.42 euros.
Goldman Sachs increased its share-price estimate on the luxury-
goods maker to 88.51 euros from 70.40 euros.  To contact the reporter on this story:
 Francesca Cinelli  in Milan at 
 fcinelli@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
David Merritt at   dmerritt1@bloomberg.net . 